description.text:
This is the result of an invitation for our department to be involved in an Engineering sponsored Sumo-bot competition. The rules are fairly simple.

  • Maximum weight is 12 lbs
  • Maximum voltage is 16
  • Maximum size not to exceed 600 mm in X, Y, and Z.
  • No pneumatic or hydraulic components
  • Offensive device energy limited to throwing or flipping limited to 600 mm high or 600 mm distance

Represented here is basic platform for mounting defensive and offensive systems to. This part of the project is ongoing and has been revised several times, though the basic design has been to make it a defensive design from the beginning.

Available here https://armattanproductions.com/pages/kit_detail/1644 are prefabricated upper, lower, and inner side panels from 3mm carbon fiber.

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2 mm

Infill:

30 - 100 %

Notes:

Most everything has been printed with 4 upper and lower layers as well as perimeters. Infill has been 30% for most parts with the exception of the battery housing and its parts that were printed at 100% infill. Small parts such as spacers are also at 100%.

Print temperatures have been 225C on the hot end and 55C on the bed. All parts are in PLA from www.microcenter.com. There is a store locally, and they have the best price on PLA.

Specifications and Sources

The motor and reduction tranmission come from a cordless drill sold by Harbor Freight https://www.harborfreight.com/18-volt-38-in-cordless-drilldriver-with-keyless-chuck-21-clutch-settings-62873.html?utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=4717b_preview&utm_source=1021&cid=mEmail_s1021_c4717b_preview&sfid= and modified according to http://www.wa4dsy.com/robot/drill-motor-hack. This mod works pretty good and is an inexpensive and effective way to get your bot moving. However, I did find that under stall loads the rubber O-ring failed. So I opted to remove the O-ring and install M5 x 6 mm flat tipped set screws in place where the clutch ball bearings were. No need to drill the holes just tap with M5. You can just run the screws in without tapping but I was not happy with the amount of stress placed in the gearbox housing. Total cost for 16 of these set screws was $1. You can get the drill motors when they go on sale for $15.99 each plus tax.

For controlling the motors I wanted a speed control that had plenty of amp capability, but did not want to break the bank. I found these on Banggood https://www.banggood.com/ESC-Brushed-Speed-Controller-for-RC-Car-Truck-Boat-320A-7_2V-16V-p-915276.html?rmmds=myorder and gave them a try. So far the only feature about them I do not like is that you cannot go from forward to reverse instantly. There is a brake feature that acts like a cycle that it has to go through before going in the opposite direction. This means allowing the motor to stop first then go. It may only be a minor annoyance. Total for ESCs was $24.83

For a battery I selected a 5000 mAh 3s battery from Hobby King https://hobbyking.com/en_us/turnigy-graphene-5200mah-3s-15c-w-xt60.html with shipping cost $43.28. I choose this battery for its more brick like shape, which fit into the design concept that I was aiming for.

Add in some XT60 connectors https://www.banggood.com/5X-XT60-Male-Female-Bullet-Connectors-Plugs-For-RC-Battery-p-916559.html?rmmds=search&cur_warehouse=CN for $4.19

Part of this project is made from aluminum sheet. You need 4 sq. feet of 1/8" 6061-T6. I have access to a water jet and cut the plates for the body and gears. I found it for as low as $38.24 at https://www.midweststeelsupply.com/store/index.php plus shipping. If you live local to a source they often have drops, which are cut offs from previous orders that can be had at a discount.

Add a 2 Kg spool of PLA for the 3D printed parts. That's $14.99.

Now we need to discuss fasteners
Battery Box -
4 - M3 x 10 Flat Head Socket Head Machine Screws to retain the catch assemblies $0.04 each. Total $0.16 http://www.mrmetric.com/M10537
6 - M3 x 14 Socket Head Cap Screws to attach battery cover to housing are $0.07 each for a total of $0.42 http://www.mrmetric.com/M10607

Sprocket Attachment -
30 - M3 x 20 Button Head Cap Screw at $0.08 each for a total of $2.40 http://www.mrmetric.com/M11498 for attaching the 24T sprockets to the back of each wheel.

Body Assembly
46 - M5 x 12 Flat Socket Head Screws. Alloy steel are $0.09 each for a total of $4.14 http://www.mrmetric.com/M10426 These attach the upper and lower plates to the 3D printed parts.

Drive Plate Assembly
12 - M5 x 20 Flat Socket Head Screws. Alloy steel are $0.07 each for a total of $0.84 http://www.mrmetric.com/M10429 . These attach the inner side plates to the main body.

16 - M5 x 50 Flat Socket Head Screws. Allow steel are $0.40 each for a total of $6.40 http://www.mrmetric.com/M10491 These attach the outer side plate and chain idlers to the inner side plate.

So the total from Mr. Metric is $15.22 plus $7.50 flat rate shipping is $22.72
Some additional fastener materials are required that can be obtained from Mcmaster-Carr. They are as follows

Idler Wheels
4 - 8 mm x 50 mm Shoulder Screws are $2.92 each totaling $11.68 https://www.mcmaster.com/#92981a207/=1adryye These are installed in the Idler Shaft Blocks prior to their assembly into the main body.

25 Roller Chain x 4 ft is $20.56 https://www.mcmaster.com/#6261k171/=1ads5cy . This is broken up into two 21" long loops. One for each side, driving the idler wheels with the driven wheel.

Total from Mcmaster is $32.24. Shipping will be an additional amount.

So far, we are up to $213.47

Wheels and Tires

Just a note about the three different drive wheel files;

  1. Drive_Wheel_x2.stl
    This is the original wheel design concept. You simply run a 3/8-24 tap inside and the wheel threads directly on the the output shaft of the gearbox. Then install the LH retaining screw that you removed when uninstalling the chuck from the cordless drill. The retention method is sound and secure if you are not driving too hard.

  2. DriveWheel-1.9mm_x2.stl
    This wheel is the same concept as above except for 1.9 mm is removed from the back face to accommodate the variations in cordless drill models offered at Harbor Freight.

  3. Drive_Wheel_alternate_x2.stl
    This is the improved design that also requires a lathe turned piece that makes the threads secure. I found that aggressive driving led to wearing on the plastic threads. I will post a pdf file detail sheet to manufacture the metal hub part to.

title: 3Racing Sakura D4 AWD base for extra receiver/gyro

description.text:
In my Sakura D4 AWD, I decided I wanted to try another RC and gyro without removing the one I had. There really wasn't any room, with the servo, ESC and battery taking all space in the lower deck and the belt forbidding anything in the upper deck. So, I designed this base.

What you will need:
-2 M4X40 screws
-4 M4 nuts
-6 M4 washers
-2 M5 washers

Don't print topbottom file, it's just to show how they are assembled.

Print top and bottom parts.

Installation instructions:

First, hold upside down the screws and insert a M4 washer to each and let it drop to the head. Then, insert them in the middle holes of the upper deck (like in the pictures). Insert the bottom part and secure it with a M4 washer and a nut for each screw. Then, insert the top part on the screws. Secure it with a M5 washer, then a M4 washer and then a nut for each screw (perhaps you will not need both washers). Put double sided tape on top and then mount your receivers/gyros/etc.

It is surprisingly stable and very convenient.

The heads of the screws decrease the battery compartment's height a bit, from 29 to 25mm, so some batteries won't fit, while with others with tight fit, you'll have to take care while installing/removing.

Have fun!

description.text:
I will upload photos of supports on my printer soon.  
I wanted to improve my Prusa I3's z-axis rigidity without having to disassemble my XY bed and/or replace pre-existing parts. I designed these angled supports to attach to the M10 y-axis threaded rod, and the top of the I3 plate. the upper support also has 8mm holes so it can double as a filament spool support. See instructions for BOM required for this upgrade.  
This upgrade is also great for squaring up and adjusting your Y and Z axes!

BOM
~1m m6 threaded rod
x8 m6 nuts
x8 m6 washers
x4 m4 x 20mm cap screws Instructions:
  • Print off parts
  • Remove m10 nuts from y-axis rods from printer and test fit parts to ensure correct angles. Also, measure required lengths of m6 rod (should be ~375mm).
  • Cut rod to length (I used a metal hacksaw)
  • (OPTIONAL) insert spool holder supports into upper angle bracket holes.
  • Test fit again with cut to length support rod.
  • insert m6 nuts into upper angled support nut-trap, screw in m6 support rod.
  • assemble and tighten all nuts.
  • Print off a test part to ensure that your Y and Z axes are perpendicular. If not, adjust by tightening/loosening angle support rod tension at bottom angle brackets.

The goal of my chain links project was to make something that could be made as one print, and be interlocked with other pieces. This first attempt worked, however I had to cut two links out of the final model since they printed inside of each other, and snapped apart when I broke the raft off the model. Cleanup of each link isn't perfect, partly since they are so small and the file we have it very large comparatively. We didn't have any sand paper so i gave up on cleaning the links any more. Based off what I've learned with this model, I'm thinking it should be possible to print rotating parts in one go, using support material to keep things together.

description.text:
This is a FPV-quadcopter shaped reflector for showing your love for the hobby and staying visible during winter commuting. Select one of the three options for attaching the reflector: ball chain, 30mm safety-pin or velcrostrap. Simply print out the body, cut 3.5 cm circles of reflective tape (8 pieces to make both sides reflective) and attach the prop discs to the body with M2x5mm or M2x6mm screws. When using elastic filaments the screws will stay in place without nuts, but with rigid filaments it might be useful to use M2 nuts in the nut traps. You will also need to drill the holes to 2mm to make room for the screws if using rigid filaments.

Banggood sells reflective tapes in all colors (e.g. SKU 1038049). These tapes are cheap, but they are relatively thin and not the most reflective tapes you can get. If you are serious about staying visible, source a piece of 3M Diamond Grade DG3 tape. This tape is amazingly reflective and strong, but unfortunately also very expensive.   2. Change the parameters to fit your tools (see the image with named dimensions)
  3. The hole for the blade part goes all the way through the carousel. Make sure the larger portion of the hole for the handle isn't so deep that the tool protrudes through the bottom of the base!
  4. Change the numTools parameter to set the number of tool holes
  5. Done!

title: Power supply cover with fused outlets

description.text:
This is the 3rd version of a project that started about 4 years ago and was followed by an improved version a few months later.

I have used these power supply covers with all my 3D printers and Laser engravers in the past years and did not see any need for improvements ... until, one day, I created a short in one of the attached the power cables. As these cables were only used on a device using less than 2A, they were dimensioned accordingly - so the short did not burn the fuse of the powerful 30A PSU, but rather caused the relatively thin cable to start burning withing seconds...

That's when I realized how dangerous a powerful PSU can be, if used without a fuse that is dimensioned according to the actual intended use. The built-in fuse or over-current protection which traps only when the maximum amperage of the power supply is exceeded will not prevent damage to attached circuits which only use a fraction of the maximum possible amperage.

So this is why I went back to look at the design of my power supply cover again, this time with the aim of protecting each power outlet with its own fuse, whose value can then be chosen to fit the current used by the attached circuits.

In this version of the project I added an automotive fuse holder for each of the 3 power outlets. These fuse holders use standard medium size blade fuses and can be ordered cheaply from eBay or AliExpress (I paid USD 1.06 per lot of 5). These fuse holders come also with a plastic cover, which we don't use here to save space. Instead of wiring the 12V output directly to the Molex or Tamiya sockets, the PSU 12V output now goes first through the fuse and only then into the socket. This allows us to protect each 12V output with a fuse that is specific to the intended use of the outlet. In my unit here, I have protected the three outlets with 15A, 10A and 5A fuses, respectively. Thus, the heatbed will be connected to the 15A outlet at the left and the extruder and motors to the 10A outlet in the middle. The 5A outlet at the right is a spare output that can be used to attach other gadgets.

ANother enhancement made in this version is to provide a choice of AC power switches. In addition to the small 10mm x 15mm rocker switch used in the previous version, the bigger 15mm x 21mm switch is now also supported.

For all the rest, this version is identical to the previous version, so please refer to there for further information on this project.

In the files section, you will find the fully parameterized OpenScad source together with ready-to-print STL files for Molex and Tamiya connectors, in versions with and without fuse holder, and for 10x15mm and 15x21mm AC rocker switches. Note that for the Molex versions you also need to print the corresponding clips, and for Tamiya versions the corresponding frame object is needed.

Note that I myself only use the Molex version of this project. While I also try to keep the
Tamiya versions updated, I have not actually built them, so I cannot guarantee that they will work perfectly.

Assembly

As the space is rather tight, one has to pay attention in which order to assemble the various components and connectors. So here is the assembly order which worked best for me:

  1. Insert 3-digit voltmeter and temporarily fix it with tape on the outside.
  2. Insert empty Molex connectors and secure them with the printed clips.
  3. Insert and screw on the fuse holders which already have the wire with the molex contact and the wire with the ferule that is screwed to the PSU. Check the proper seating of the Molex clips while nserting the fuse holder - it's tight!
  4. Insert and screw on the AC socket with the GND and N wires arleady soldered on.
  5. Insert the AC rocker switch with the L wire going to the PSU and a wire going to the AC socket that ends in a 6.3mm blade connector.
  6. If applicable, insert the small prototype board with the remote trimpot and adjust the position for the trimpot to be accessible through the hole.
  7. Secure the 3-digit voltmeter and (if applicable) the trimpot PCB with the hot glue pistol.
  8. Add the GND wires with the molex contacts on one side and the feruls on the other.
  9. Firmly screw on all the feruled wires going to the PSU.
  10. Check and recheck for proper connections before powering the first time.
  11. Once all is functioning well, put the cover onto the PSU and secure it with the 2 lateral screws.

Maker juholga already created some additional modules for the tool rack that I've also printed and now I'd like to add some designs of my own. More designs may be added later.

description.text:
Introduction

This Gizmo was made for a Louis Poulsen lamp that we recently bought. The lamp had 3 small (2mm) holes drilled into it, and I thought that it would be cool to add some personality to the lamp.

The design that I went for was something that would look and feel like something from the Fallout Games. Like something from the Nuclear Space Age.

The Design

The plan when designing this thing was to have nuts to fasten the top screw, and also have the spacers slide into indents made for them. But the supports filled out the indentations for the spacers, and the holes for the screws were tight enough to be threaded by the screws themselves, so no nuts are necessary.

Parts needed

See image above for reference
Screws:
4pcs M3x6
1pcs M4x20

Spacers:
2pcs M3x15 + 6
2pcs M3x15

Fastening the Gizmo to the lamp

There's a small nub on the bottom of the bottom part, which slid through the hole in the lampshade. To fasten the Gizmo a small burning torch was used to heat up a screw. You can then "rivet" the Gizmo on the inside of the lampshade by pressing the hot screw against the plastic, thus melting it as a rivet.

description.text: If you like your resistor and diode leads to be bent uniformly and consistently, then this tool is for you.  It also provides a useful task for the wee little ones in the house who want to assist you with your electronics projects.

There are three mix-and-match styles to the supplied STL files: metric vs. imperial, narrow vs. wide, and long vs. short. The significance of these three styles are, metric: lead spacings in increments of 2 millimeters
imperial: lead spacings in increments of 0.05 inches narrow: for small resistors whose bodies are no longer than 6.75 mm (0.25 inches)
wide: for medium resistors whose bodies are no longer than 10.50 mm (0.40 inches) long: a long tool with lead spacings up to 40 mm (1.5 inches)
short: a shorter tool with lead spacings up to 30 mm (1.0 inch) The two OpenSCAD source files are nearly identical with the only difference being that one has settings for metric units whilst the other imperial. As the files are fully parameterized: it is easy to change the increments, dimensions, spacings, widths, etc. of the tools by editing the OpenSCAD files and then re-rendering the tools.

comments.text: PCB layout designers are free to use whatever lead spacing they want, regardless of the component size.  (And yes, you can even make the lead spacing narrower than the component's length which is where you end up with resistors mounted standing up on end.)  One classic example is when you straddle a resistor over several traces in which case you may end up with lead spacing wider than otherwise normal.  That's done to avoid use of a via. Another common case is when you make your own PCBs: it's a lot easier to drill a series of holes which are all lined up nicely.  As such, you may make the lead spacing the same for several resistors and, say, diodes even if the spacings are wider than normal for some of the components.

I remixed this from MechEngBot's pour nozzle as that model had an odd thread and cap size, so I swapped the threads with Bottle Threads from makerwiz's post. After a quick run through NetFabb the final model prints fairly well with 100% fill and standard settings in PLA. My Ultimaker has a bit of a hard time with the overhangs at the top of the bottom threads and leaves a lot of string, but after some clean up the end result is pretty strong. I suppose I could extend this portion a bit to give it less overhang, but I'll leave that for the next hobbyist... Enjoy!

description.text: This is a rerailer for Lionel O27 Track. I didn't see any rerailers for O scale in train stores or websites so I thought it would be trivial to design one. It was anything but trivial. This design seems to work. It will handle a set of wheels off track, not a whole truck off track. I built it narrow so that it would fit between 2 sets of parallel tracks. Cars will make a sound as they pass over but that adds realism to the layout.

You need to print 2 to get a complete rerailer. Additional Parts list: 2 small wood screws (#4x3/4") or 2 small nails. Assembly instructions: Put one piece on one side of a piece of straight track, and the other opposite it. You might have to push a little to get them in place. It will work better if you screw them down (if you have wood beneath the track). Printing instructions: The parts were printed on a Makerbot Replicator2
  • PLA (Makerbot filament)
  • Printed: Low(faster) resolution, 8% infill, 2 shells, 0.30 mm layer height, 230C
    • Some best practices for printing:
  • optimize print parameters for your printer, filament, etc (only you can determine the best parameters)
  • use good filament
  • level your build plate prior to printing complex parts. it's worth the few minutes it takes. always level after removing tape, or if pulling hard to remove a part.
  • make sure the build plate is clean.
  • if using blue tape, stretch it tight when applying it to the build plate.
  • if you have small holes in the blue tape, print the thing in a good section of the tape.
  • pre-feed the filament 30 to 60-s before printing (i.e., run load for 30-60s)
  • do not print several complicated parts in one build (do complex parts by themselves)
  • I find that printing faster is better (probably so the filament can't ball up in one spot)
  • make sure that there aren't any obstructions on the spool, such as some filament used to hold it in place during shipping
  • when the filament spool gets low, the filament can be tightly wound on the spool and the filament may not feed properly... take special care...
  • when a new spool is used, it is easy for the filament to jump outside the spool and then it will bind up later around the spool holder ruining your build
  • make sure it is easy for the filament to enter the filament feed tube. others have designed spools, mounts, etc. for that purpose. i use a small rope that forces the filament away from the spool before entering the filament feed tube.
  • if you hear clicking when printing, that may be a result of the filament wrapped around the spool and not feeding
  • for the replicaor2, look at the blob a filament in the left front part of the build plate and then the trail of filament to the biuild location. there should be a glob, and the line of filament should be continuous and smooth
  • one way to remove parts when using blue tape is to use a very thin spatula bought in craft-art stores (advice from youtube). get one with a wide, blunt front end (not long and thin). mine is 11 mils thick (0.011") and 20-mm wide at the front. a painting spatula/scraper in hardware stores won't work and may damage the build plate. (I use blue tape so I don't have any best practices for bare plates, heated plates or for other tapes like mylar)
  • perform regular maintenance (grease, etc).
  • when I continued to have problems printing even after performing maintenance, following troublshooting instructions, changing filaments, cleaning gears, cleaning everything, optimizing print parameters, changing temperatures, etc., I bought a new extruder assembly from Makerbot and it solved all of my problems.

Print your own dice!!!!

A dice can sound something really simple but it also something very significant and if you don’t have board games you will be most likely to not have a dice. Also, in my home with assigning different tasks to preform in the apartment a dice can be ideally because we can numerate each task and then each one will through the dice and complete the corresponding task. A dice can also be an alternative to play rock scissors paper.

Steps to Build your own dice:

1) Build a center rectangle in my plane and the dimensions were 3.00inx3.00in.
2) Extruded all dimensions of the rectangle in order to have a symmetrical cube.
3) Numerate each side of the dice with the numbers from one through six. Generally, in most of the dices the numbers are simply black holes (not hollow).
4) To make hollow holes start extruding the holes with a distance of -0.1in so the cut goes through the inside.
5) Use the shell tool in order to fulfill the hollow cut. I repeated the process for all of the faces of the cube. Then, to make the dice less squared and shape rounded.

Based on Roboduck's Portal Gun ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:8809 ), this is a full scale portal gun sliced into pieces which will fit into a 130x130x130mm build volume. On most of the pieces I included pegs and sockets to help align the assembly. I did this as a prop for a costume. It's not perfect, because I didn't have time to clean up all the parts or reprint ones which have holes or other imperfections. This model requires a crazy amount of filament, and a solid week of printing.

You're not going to be insane enough to print this monster. But here's what I did: Print all the parts. Assemble and glue. Paint with an ABS + acetone mixture to give a more uniform surface and more strength.  
The "wires" are made of black quarter-inch tube, available at any hardware store.

Note that the 2 internal pillars can actually be cut off now as the mounting holes inside are fused to the top of the part. this helps improve airflow even further.

Classic coffee mug designed to be printed with Proto Pasta HTPLA V3 filament. HTPLA stand for high temp PLA this means that it can be heat treated in the oven for greater strength and temperature resistance. Follow the instructions at https://www.proto-pasta.com/collections/high-performance-htpla . I will update this post to share how its holding up and maybe some tips from what I learn. 130% up scale for real size.

Update: After printing at .15mm resolution I left the supports in and placed it in a standard home oven at 250 for about an hour. While the heat treating process was taking place the support material deformed after about a half hour but the handle and mug body remained intact. (ProtoPasta recommends 100% infill for best results when heat treating)
The mug can withstand extremely hot temperatures and holds liquids with ease. I suggest adjusting the support angle to 55 degrees to minimize support defects toward the bottom of the mug and still allow enough support for the handle.

title: HTC Vive Base Station Mount Flat extension to be used with double sided tape

description.text:
HTC Vive comes with mounts for base station that needs to be mounted using screws. I am renting a place, and drilling walls is not possible. I wanted to use some kind of double sided tape to mount base stations on a wall. The problem is that stock mounts have a very low surface area on it's back, which makes really bad adhesion to a wall. To make it stick very well you need as much of the surface as possible. This extension gives me large surface area.

I've used heavy duty good mounting strips like these https://www.commandbrand.com.au/3M/en_AU/command-au/products/~/Command-Large-Refill-Strips-6pk-17023P?N=5924736+3294529197+3294773680&rt=rud#variation1 from 3M Command Brand. I've used ones rated for 2.9KG. The base station is around 100g, but CG is away from the wall and it pulls the top part of mount out, not down. Anyway, it seems it's holding the weight of base station with 2 strips applied. Before trusting mounts to hold real base stations I hang dummy load to test adhesion for a couple of hours. I also followed instruction on the package (wait for 1 hour before applying a load)

I've used 2 10mm M4 bolts with nuts. It designed that you can take mounting station off the extension without removing the extension from the wall.

I am not responsible for any damage your station might get from falling down using this extension.

title: G27 Splitter Shifter for Truck Simulator (Euro / American)

description.text:
Recently been playing a bit of euro truck sim, of course semis have a 12+ speed transmission, and use 2 sets of splitters, one for half gears and one for high and low range.

Easy enough fix, you can pick up a replacement knob wire it in in a afternoon and your done. Knobs are expensive and slow to ship though.

3d printing to the rescue! Sub 2 hour print, will get you not only a better shaped shift knob but also those precious splitters. This will utilize two small (19x12mm) typical rocker switches and mount to the g27 shiftier. You will have to wire them to the 4 lowest red buttons on the g27 (disassembly of shiftier is required) by simply using the ground pad and wiring to the line of 4 resistors that control those buttons - I recommend 2 and 4 or 1 and 3 if counting left to right, if you use 3 and 4 or 1 and 2 you trigger both buttons at the same time will activate the hardware override to change the degrees of motion so don't do that.

You may need to do some trimming to get the rockers to fit snugly but they shouldn't give you to much guff. You will also need to drill a hole in the surround under the shift boot to feed the new wires to the knob so they don't interfere with shifting. And you may need to bore out the boot collar so you can snake the wires through it. In the end you should have a factory looking shifter with a knob with two rockers! Because this shfit knob doesn't use the OEM set screw on the shifter I recommend wrapping 1 or 2 wraps of electrical tape around the shaft after the boot is in place and slide the shifter over that, it should fit nice and tight alternatively you can use glue if your confident you wont want to remove it.

In case you have any issues I've uploaded the source fusion 360 file.
